    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27a.8-9_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">8</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        Public Library
                        Springfield, Missouri
                        Friday 1:53<hi rend="caps">P.M.</hi> 4/24, 1959.
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Bard:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>How careless of me to lose your address. However, my last letter reached you, so I trust this will too.</p>
                
                <p>Just now I finished rereading "The Song of Jed Smith". I want to say that it was very gripping. The highlights were the coming upon the Indian village, the interpolate account of the death of Silas Gobel, the mule going over the precipice, and the cutting the throat of the raon horse. It was quite a trek. It was very clever of you to facilitate the meter by calling him "Dioh".</p>
                
                <p>Do you ever do the Double Crosti<del/><add>s</add> in the Saturday Review of <hi rend="caps">N.Y.</hi> times? Some 4 years ago I started <unclear>working</unclear> them. I solved all the back numbers of the "Review" from 1946. Then I bought 10 or 12
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27a.8-9_0002"/>
                
                    books of them from Simon and Schuster. I solve from 3 to 5 a day. Just lately, however, I ran out of crostics so am now reading some Series #42 will be out in 4 or 5 weeks, so Mrs. Doris Nash Wortman told me in a letter this week.</p>
                    
                <p>Did I tell you? I am a victim of Parkinson's disease. I still walk about as well as ever. My left hand is almost useless. My speech is a mess. For 8 years I taught in Missouri high schools. Then for 11 years I worked as a janitor in a big furniture factory. I now draw Social Security and a total disability benefit &#8212; $96.00 per month. I am 57 years old.</p>
                
                <p>Since 1936 I have had printed 5 books of down to earth poems of which 9000 copies have been sold. I have 4 or 5 copies of my last edition left. If you care for a copy, I will mail you one.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Love,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Perry Mason.</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
